00:01:54.180 --> 00:01:56.813
that means that two a is negative two,

00:01:56.813 --> 00:01:58.828
two a is equal to negative two

00:01:58.828 --> 00:02:01.648
or a is equal to negative one.

00:02:01.648 --> 00:02:02.559
Another way to think about it,

00:02:02.559 --> 00:02:07.549
your a is going to be half of
your first degree coefficient

00:02:07.549 --> 00:02:09.341
or the coefficient on the x term.

00:02:09.341 --> 00:02:11.013
So the coefficient of the
x term is a negative two,

00:02:11.013 --> 00:02:13.214
half of that is a negative one.

00:02:13.214 --> 00:02:14.925
And then we wanna have,

00:02:14.925 --> 00:02:19.443
and then we want to have an a squared.

00:02:19.443 --> 00:02:22.425
So if a is negative one, a
squared would be plus one.

00:02:22.425 --> 00:02:24.758
So let's throw a plus one there.

00:02:24.758 --> 00:02:25.990
But like we've done and said before,

00:02:25.990 --> 00:02:28.382
we can't just willy-nilly add something

00:02:28.382 --> 00:02:30.817
on one side of equation
without adding it to the other

00:02:30.817 --> 00:02:33.730
or without subtracting it
again on that same side.

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:37.372
Otherwise, you're fundamentally changing

00:02:37.372 --> 00:02:39.137
the truth of the equation.

00:02:39.137 --> 00:02:41.989
So if I add one on that side,
I even have to add one on the,

00:02:41.989 --> 00:02:43.050
if I add one of the left side,

00:02:43.050 --> 00:02:44.652
I even have to add one on the right side

00:02:44.652 --> 00:02:46.384
to make the equation still hold true

00:02:46.384 --> 00:02:50.518
or I could add one and subtract
one from the left-hand side,

00:02:50.518 --> 00:02:53.429
so I'm not really changing the
value of the left-hand side.

00:02:53.429 --> 00:02:54.717
All I've done is added one

00:02:54.717 --> 00:02:57.320
